## 5. Functional Requirements

### FR-01: Multi-Layer Detection Pipeline

System shall implement three detection layers executed in sequence:

```
Layer 1: Passive Analysis (always runs, no user prompt)
  → Texture analysis: micro-texture patterns on real skin vs printed/screen surfaces
  → Reflection analysis: screen glare, matte vs specular surface reflection
  → Colour space analysis: RGB vs YCbCr anomalies common in digital faces

Layer 2: Active Challenge-Response (if Layer 1 confidence < 0.90)
  → Randomised prompt selection from pool of 8+ actions
  → Examples: "Look left", "Blink twice", "Open mouth", "Nod slowly"
  → Prompts are randomised to prevent pre-recorded response attacks
  → Response must occur within a time window (1.5–3 seconds per prompt)

Layer 3: Temporal Consistency Analysis (always runs on captured frames)
  → Analyse 15+ frames across the session for deepfake artifact signatures
  → Check for: edge distortions at face boundary, lighting inconsistency across frames,
    A/V synchronisation anomalies, unnatural smoothness in skin texture over time
```

- System shall produce a single composite `liveness_score` (0.00–1.00) from all active layers
- System shall classify result as: `REAL` (≥0.85) / `REVIEW` (0.70–0.84) / `FAKE` (<0.70)
- System shall log which layer(s) contributed to the score for explainability

### FR-02: Adversarial Attack Detection

System shall specifically detect and flag:

| Attack Type | Detection Signal | Action |
|-------------|-----------------|--------|
| Print attack | Flat texture, no subsurface light scatter, no micro-movement | Flag as FAKE |
| Screen replay | RGB colour shift, screen glare, pixel grid at zoom | Flag as FAKE |
| Real-time deepfake overlay | Edge artifacts at face boundary, lighting inconsistency, temporal glitches | Flag as FAKE / REVIEW |
| Injection attack | Device signal validation: cryptographic proof image originated from hardware camera | Flag as FAKE if signal absent |

### FR-03: Device Signal Validation

- System shall request cryptographic attestation that video frames originated from the physical device camera (not a virtual camera plugin)
- On mobile: use iOS DeviceCheck / Android SafetyNet (Play Integrity API) to validate device integrity
- Sessions from virtual camera environments shall be automatically flagged for review
- If attestation cannot be completed (older device), system shall increase challenge-response requirements

### FR-04: Skin Tone Equity

- System shall be evaluated on Fitzpatrick Scale (I–VI) across all skin tone groups
- APCER and BPCER must not differ by more than 2 percentage points across any Fitzpatrick group
- Training dataset must include minimum 15% representation from Southeast Asian (Fitzpatrick III–IV) skin tones
- Monthly bias audit required post-launch using production session data

### FR-05: Human Review Queue

- Sessions scoring 0.70–0.84 shall be placed in a REVIEW queue visible to compliance team
- Queue shall display: video clip of session, confidence score, breakdown of signals that triggered review, attack type hypothesis
- Compliance officer can approve / reject with a 1-click decision + mandatory reason selection
- Queue must show SLA countdown (target: reviewed within 2 hours during business hours)

### FR-06: Verdict Webhooks

System shall fire webhook events for every liveness decision:

**`liveness.passed`** — score ≥ 0.85, auto-approved
**`liveness.review_required`** — score 0.70–0.84, queued for human review
**`liveness.failed`** — score < 0.70, auto-rejected
**`liveness.manual_approved`** — human reviewer approved a REVIEW session
**`liveness.manual_rejected`** — human reviewer rejected a REVIEW session

