## 6. AI Model Specification

> **This section exists so PM, Engineering, and stakeholders have shared alignment on the AI design decisions — not because PM implements the model.**

### 6.1 Model Architecture Options

| Approach | How It Works | Pros | Cons | Recommended? |
|----------|-------------|------|------|-------------|
| Rule-based heuristics | Hardcoded rules: blink detection, texture threshold | Fast, explainable | Brittle, easy to defeat | ❌ Layer 1 supplement only |
| Binary classifier (CNN) | Train on real vs fake face images | Well-studied, good baseline | Static — fails on new deepfake techniques | ✅ Layer 1 base model |
| Vision Transformer (ViT) | Attention-based, captures long-range spatial patterns | Better on subtle artifacts | Compute-heavy, needs more data | ✅ Layer 3 temporal analysis |
| Ensemble (CNN + ViT + heuristics) | Combine outputs with learned weights | Higher accuracy, harder to fool | Complex to maintain | ✅ **Recommended architecture** |

### 6.2 Training Data Requirements

| Dataset | Source | Purpose |
|---------|--------|---------|
| FaceForensics++ | TU Munich (academic) | Deepfake training data — 1,000 videos with 4 manipulation methods |
| DFDC (Deepfake Detection Challenge) | Facebook AI | 100,000+ videos, diverse demographics |
| NUAA (Imposter Dataset) | Academic | Print attack and replay attack samples |
| **SEA Supplement (custom)** | Collected from consenting users | Fitzpatrick III–IV skin tones, SEA lighting conditions, mid-range Android cameras |

> **Critical PM decision:** Off-the-shelf datasets are majority Caucasian/Western. A model trained only on these will have higher BPCER for SEA users — i.e., it will unfairly reject real Thai/Cambodian users more often. Custom data collection is non-negotiable for this market.

### 6.3 Confidence Threshold Rationale

```
Why 0.85 for auto-approve?

The threshold defines the product's risk tolerance.

If threshold = 0.70:
  → More users auto-approved (lower friction)
  → More sophisticated deepfakes get through (higher fraud risk)

If threshold = 0.95:
  → Almost no deepfakes get through (very secure)
  → Significantly more real users rejected or sent to manual review (high friction, high cost)

0.85 is the recommended starting point based on:
  - ISO/IEC 30107-3 Level 2 compliance requires APCER < 5%
  - Business tolerance for manual review queue (targeting < 10% of sessions)
  - Pilot data should inform re-calibration after 30 days

This threshold must be a product decision, not a default engineering constant.
Threshold changes should require PM + Risk sign-off.
```

### 6.4 Model Degradation & Retraining Policy

| Trigger | Action |
|---------|--------|
| APCER rises > 7% in any 7-day rolling window | Immediate alert to ML team + PM |
| New deepfake attack technique detected in fraud queue | Emergency retrain sprint initiated |
| Quarterly scheduled review | Evaluate model performance on new attack samples |
| Bias audit shows > 2% BPCER variance across Fitzpatrick groups | Retrain with corrected dataset |

> **Why this matters:** AI models in adversarial settings degrade. Attackers iterate. A liveness model that's effective today may be obsolete in 6 months without a retraining pipeline. PM must own the policy for when retraining happens — not leave it to engineering judgment.

### 6.5 Fallback Logic

```
IF device_attestation = FAILED
  AND liveness_score > 0.85
  → Override to REVIEW (do not auto-approve without device signal)

IF Layer 1 confidence > 0.92
  → Skip Layer 2 (active challenge) to reduce friction for clearly real users

IF processing_time > 8 seconds
  → Return partial result, escalate to REVIEW
  → Do not timeout user — show "Processing…" state

IF model inference service is unavailable
  → Route all sessions to human review queue
  → Do NOT fail-open (auto-approve) — fail-secure (require review)
```

